Q9. Difference Between Primary Key and Foreign Key

Primary Key:
Uniquely identifies each record in a table.
Cannot contain NULL values.
A table can have only one primary key.
Ensures entity integrity.

Foreign Key:
Refers to the primary key in another table.
Can contain duplicate and NULL values (depending on constraint).
A table can have multiple foreign keys.
Maintains referential integrity between tables.



Q10. What Are Constraints in SQL and Why Are They Used?

Constraints are rules applied to table columns to enforce data integrity and accuracy in a database.

Common Types:

PRIMARY KEY – Ensures unique and non-null values.

FOREIGN KEY – Maintains relationship between tables.

NOT NULL – Prevents NULL values.

UNIQUE – Ensures all values are different.

CHECK – Restricts values based on a condition.

DEFAULT – Assigns a default value if none is provided.

Why Used?

To maintain data accuracy.

To prevent invalid data entry.

To enforce business rules.

To ensure consistency and reliability of the database.
